### Description

the value passed to the directive's input property is not set when the directive is assigned to a host element in a `@Component` decorator using a `hostDirectives` array

```
@Component({
hostDirectives: [
    {
      directive: CdkDrag,
      inputs:[
        'cdkDragBoundary:"body"' // doesn't work. see line:62 inside ngOninit method
      ]
    },
  ],

})

ngOnInit():void{
this._cdkDrag.boundaryElement = 'body'; // !!!it works this way!!!
}
```

### Reproduction

StackBlitz link: https://stackblitz.com/~/github.com/evheniyrz/angular-cdk-drag-handle
GitHub link: https://github.com/evheniyrz/angular-cdk-drag-handle
Steps to reproduce:
1. Create a draggable component
2. Set the directive - `CdkDrag` - to the component host using the component decorator property - `hostDirectives`
3. Set values for directive input properties

```
@Component({
hostDirectives: [
    {
      directive: CdkDrag,
      inputs:[
        'cdkDragBoundary:"body"'
      ]
    },
  ],

})
```


### Expected Behavior

the dragged element is limited to the value set to the property - `cdkDragBoundary`

### Actual Behavior

The draggable element is not bound to the value set for the directive's input property - `cdkDragBoundary`

### Environment

- Angular:
"@angular/core": "^17.3.1", "@angular/cli": "^17.3.1",
- CDK/Material:
- "@angular/cdk": "^17.3.1", "@angular/material": "^17.3.1",
- Browser(s): any
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): any

### Documentation Feedback

The example for the form field mat-error is using a function call in the template: 
 @if (email.invalid) {
      <mat-error>{{getErrorMessage()}}</mat-error>
    }
Best practices mentions to avoid using function calls in templates, but the documentation contains this example since the Material version 5. After all, is it correct using a function call in template for the mat-error?

### Affected documentation page

https://material.angular.io/components/form-field/overview#error-messages

